node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Wake Up, Singapore 🇸🇬 on May 19, 2020. Image may contain: 1 person, text that says 'UK weather forecast: Britain to bask in 29C heatwave TOMORROW in hottest day of the year S1 *Laughs in Singaporean'

node.text: I’m from Chennai in South India and I’ve lived in Singapore long enough to experience enough summers and winters in both places. Singapore is no where close to being as bad as Chennai. The temperatures are nearly identical as both as coastal cities in the tropics but my city lies dead smack in the middle of major wind streams and it makes the coastal climate a lot more unbearably humid than it gets in Singapore. When we hit 40’C, it actually feels like we’re getting steamed at 45-50’C and that was never the case in Singapore. It’s still bearable.
@themidtownshow Because The U.K. heat is mostly from the sun whereas Singapore heat is from humidity with it being close to the equator
